# Roleplay Highlights — Session — 2026-03-24

---

## Character Voices

### Daz
- Operates in a cool, transactional register — quick to pivot when a lie collapses, never visibly flustered; treats negotiation as a puzzle to be solved in real time
- Dry wit surfaces in one-liners that land harder for being underplayed; he doesn't beg for credibility, he assumes it
- When covering for teammates (Glabbagool, Grygum), he smooths over their chaos with the polished confidence of someone who has done this before

> "I already feel the gratitude of Lolth. I have that."

> "We are not completely familiar with the spores and the mushrooms and all of that, and so it makes tactical sense for us to ask for people who have been around it more, and might understand any unwanted side effects — lest we go ahead and just blow everything up and cause us all to get infected and die."

> "Glabbagool, I'm taking care of this, it's fine."

---

### Zalthir
- Speaks rarely, acts efficiently; when he does put words together they tend to be deflections or repositions, not explanations
- Comfortable with ambiguity in his own role — "boss" lands as a functional label, not a claim of status
- Dry and self-aware in the aftermath of failed heroics; treats combat setbacks with the same level composure as successes

> "It's a good boss, yeah."

> "Yeah, yeah, totally. That, yes. It's a term they use among Dragonborn."

> "I'm out of actions and bonus actions, so I guess I'll just kind of look on and be confused."

---

### Grygum
- Swings between blunt provocation and genuine surprise that the blunt provocation worked; there's no strategy behind the taunting, just instinct
- Honest about his own expectations — he doesn't embellish his wins after the fact
- Economical in combat speech; the satisfaction is in the result, not the announcement

> "Come get it, idiot."

> "Kaboom! I didn't expect it to work."

> "That worked better than I had any right to expect."

